<h2>Hosting</h2>
<p>Three things came to mind when I thought about how to host Magenda.</p>
<ul>
	<li>It doesn't need to scale – only because it's a side project.</li>
	<li>It doesn't need a database.</li>
	<li>Performance is important.</li>
</ul>

<p>I heard deploying on Heroku was quick and simple. I hadn't used it before – so I decided to give it try. I signed up for an account and initialized a git repo. Deploying from the commandline was frightening, yet refreshing.</p>

<h3>Coding</h3>
<p>The repo was initialized. Hosting was set up. It was time to code. Form follows function, so I focused on only the later. The idea was to make it work first and table the appearance. It was a sound plan that yielded satisfying results.</p>

<p>Coding with Angular for the first time was awesome. Kind of tricky at first, but the documentation and linked console messages helped a ton. I enjoyed struggling with it for a bit, that's how you get better at anything. But it wasn't long until I had something functioning properly.</p>

<p>Yay! From there I referred to my initial sketches. Having my ideas on paper prior to development was beneficial. It made styling a piece of cake.</p>

<h3>Conclusion</h3>
<p>Building this single-page web app was awesome. I designed something new, coded with an unfamiliar frame work, and deployed with on a PaaS.</p>
<p>Heroku's free tier forces the site to sleep after a certain period of inactivity. Magenda is often slow to load for this reason. In retrospect, a different hosting provider might have been more responsive to initial requests. No big deal, that's how you learn.</p>
